## What Actually Clicked for Me

The distinction between a threat and a vulnerability clicked more clearly today than it did back on Day 13. A threat is external to the system — it is a potential cause of harm that exists regardless of whether the system has weaknesses. A vulnerability is a characteristic of the system that makes it susceptible to harm from a threat.

The practical importance of this distinction is that you can only directly control vulnerabilities, not threats. Ransomware groups exist whether or not MyClinic does anything about it. What MyClinic can control is whether OpenMRS has the vulnerabilities that would allow a ransomware attack to succeed — unpatched software, inadequate backup protection, insufficient network segmentation. Threat identification tells you what you are defending against. Vulnerability identification tells you where your defenses are weak.

Another thing that clicked is that the threat and vulnerability analysis is not a one-time exercise. The threat landscape changes — new vulnerability classes are discovered, new attack techniques emerge, new threat actors emerge. The vulnerability landscape changes too — new software versions introduce new weaknesses, configuration drift creates new exposure, staff turnover changes the insider threat picture. This analysis needs to be revisited periodically, which connects directly to the continuous monitoring strategy from Day 30.

