## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2021 Eskenazi Health breach** in Indianapolis — a ransomware attack that forced the hospital system to divert ambulances and cancel elective procedures. What made the Eskenazi case particularly instructive is the post-incident disclosure about the attack timeline.

The attackers had been present in Eskenazi's network for approximately six weeks before the ransomware payload was deployed. During those six weeks they moved laterally, escalated privileges, identified backup systems, and positioned themselves to maximize the impact of the final attack — including compromising the backup infrastructure before triggering encryption to eliminate the recovery option.

That six-week dwell time maps directly to the vulnerability categories I identified today. The initial access was through a phishing email — V-012. The lateral movement was enabled by inadequate network segmentation and overly permissive access controls — V-005, V-008. The backup compromise was possible because backup systems were accessible from the compromised environment — V-014. The monitoring gaps — V-009 — allowed the six-week presence to go undetected.

The Eskenazi case is a useful reminder that ransomware attacks are not single events — they are multi-stage campaigns where each stage depends on specific vulnerabilities being present and undetected. Addressing any one of those vulnerabilities — better monitoring that detects lateral movement, network segmentation that limits where an attacker can go after initial access, backup isolation that prevents the attacker from compromising the recovery option — changes the outcome even if the initial access succeeds.

