## What I Am Still Thinking About

Something I want to think more carefully about is the supply chain threat for OpenMRS specifically. The Log4Shell vulnerability in late 2021 — a critical remote code execution vulnerability in the Log4j Java logging library — affected an enormous number of Java applications because Log4j was a nearly ubiquitous dependency. OpenMRS is a Java application, and OpenMRS deployments were affected by Log4Shell.

What the Log4Shell incident illustrated is that the vulnerability surface of a complex application is not just the application code itself — it is the entire dependency tree. OpenMRS depends on dozens of Java libraries, each of which has its own vulnerability history. Tracking the vulnerability status of OpenMRS's full dependency tree, not just the core application version, is a meaningful and complex security challenge.

I want to explore what a practical approach to dependency vulnerability tracking looks like for a small clinic IT team that is not running a dedicated application security program. Tools like OWASP Dependency-Check or GitHub Dependabot provide some automated capability, but the process of integrating that into the patch management workflow for OpenMRS is something worth developing concretely.

